<DOC><DOCNO> AP880318-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2347EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Obit-Clarke     03-18 0306</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Clarke,290</SECOND><HEAD>Former Army Europe Chief, 4-Star General Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bruce G. Clarke, a retired four-star generalwho was the Army commander-in-chief in Europe when Berlin was thefocal point of the Cold War between the United States and theSoviet Union, has died. He was 86.   Clarke, who died Thursday at Walter Reed Army Hospital, hadsuffered a stroke.   The McLean, Va. resident was born in Adams, N.Y. He wasgraduated from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. in1925, and he later received a master's degree in civil engineeringfrom Cornell University and a law degree from La Salle ExtensionUniversity.   During World War II, he commanded the Combat Command A in the4th Armored Division and later commanded the division. During theKorean War, he commanded the U.S. I Corps and later the X Corps ofthe Far East Command.   Later, he commanded the U.S. Army in the Pacific, the U.S. 7thArmy in Europe and the Continental Army Command at Fort Monroe, Va.   He was commander-in-chief of the Army in Europe from 1960 to1962 and was credited with keeping his troops in a high state oftraining and morale while supervising patrols of air and groundroutes to Berlin.   Clarke devoted himself to Army affairs after retiring in 1962,writing frequently on matters such as training and command andmaking an inspection of Vietnam in 1968.   His wife, the former Bessie Mitchell, died in 1956.   He is survived by three sons _ Bruce C. Clarke Jr. of St. Antona.d. Jessnitz, Austria; Dr. David A. Clarke of Colorado Springs,Colo.; and Army Col. Gordon M. Clarke of San Antonio, Texas _ adaughter, Mrs. Elisabeth Clark of Leesburg, Va.; two sisters, MaryGriffin of Adams and Frances Saternow of Oswego, N.Y.; 18grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.</TEXT></DOC>